ant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ashton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called, especially Ashton-under-Lyne near Manchester. Most are named from Old English <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’; the one in Northamptonshire is <i>(æt thǣm) æscum</i> ‘(at the) ash trees’. Others have been assimilated to this from different sources. The one in Devon is ‘the settlement (<i>tūn</i>) of Æschere’, while the one in Hertfordshire is ‘the settlement of Ælli’."],"variants":[{"name":"Aspden","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aspden (alias Aspen) in Oswaldtwistle, Lancashire. This surname has been confused with   Ashton   and   Austin  , and probably also with   Aston   and   Astin  , all of which are common surnames in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":64,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas de Ashton I was born in 1195, in Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England, his father, Roger Wrightington de Asheton, was 30 and his mother, Alice, was 25. He married Agneta de Lathom about 1223, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1270, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1195–1270":"1195–1270","1185–1275":"1185–1275","1195–1278":"1195–1278","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1218–1300":"1218–1300","1225–1300":"1225–1300","1165–1238":"1165–1238","1170–1278":"1170–1278","1165":"1165","1275":"1275","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","about 1223":"umbes 1223","1218":"1218","Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England":"Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England","England.":"England","Ashton in Makerfield, Lancashire, England":"Ashton in Makerfield, Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"